🧮 Activity 1: Basic Calculator (Student Instructions)
📌 What you are building
You are creating a simple calculator program that:
asks the user for two numbers
performs basic maths calculations
displays the results clearly
This activity helps you practise:
variables
user input
number data types
mathematical operators
output

Step 1: Create variables to store numbers
Create two variables.
num1
num2
Each variable will store one number entered by the user.
Variables are used so the program can remember the values and use them later in calculations.
Set the initial value of each variable to 0
👉 Why this matters:
Programs cannot perform calculations unless the values are stored somewhere in memory.

Step 2: Ask the user for the numbers
Use the input function to ask the user to enter each number.
The message shown to the user should clearly explain what they are doing and what they need to type (for example, “This program is for calculating two numbers supplied by the user” and then “Enter the first number”).
👉 Why this matters:
input() allows the program to interact with the user and receive data while the program is running.

Step 3: Convert the input to numbers
Convert each user input into a floating-point number.
A floating-point number can store whole numbers and decimals.
👉 Why this matters:
The input() function always returns text (a string).
Maths operations cannot be performed on text.
Using float allows the user to enter values like 2.5, not just whole numbers.
You can nest the float function around the input function float(input())

Step 4: Perform the calculations
Use mathematical operators to calculate:
addition
subtraction
multiplication
division
Each calculation should use the two numbers entered by the user.
👉 Why this matters:
Operators tell Python what type of maths to perform.

Step 5: Display the results
Use the output function to show the result of each calculation.
Each result should clearly show:
the numbers used
the operation performed
the final answer
👉 Why this matters:
Clear output makes programs easier to understand and use.

Step 6: Handle division safely (extension)
Check that the second number is not zero before dividing.
If it is zero, display a message instead of attempting the calculation.
👉 Why this matters:
Dividing by zero causes an error and can crash the program.

✔ Success criteria
Your program is complete when it:
asks the user for two numbers
converts the input into numbers
performs all four maths operations
displays clear results
does not crash if division by zero occurs
